      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Scholars defending originalism argue that \"law office history\" is a straw man because the methodology relies on rigorous, verifiable historical evidence rather than subjective judicial preference. They contend that while critics claim judges cherry-pick facts, the actual practice involves extensive research into legislative history, dictionary definitions, and contemporary understandings to determine the text's objective meaning. Ultimately, the core justification is that this disciplined approach prevents the judiciary from imposing modern political ideologies onto the Constitution, ensuring that legal outcomes reflect the original democratic will rather than the personal biases of individual judges.",
